  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is a **solar microscope** (*zonnemicroscoop*) — essentially the world's first projector — made by **J. Mortier** in Amsterdam in 1776. A solar microscope uses sunlight reflected through a condensing lens to project hugely magnified images of microscopic specimens onto a wall or screen in a darkened room. A flea could be projected to six feet wide. These instruments were simultaneously scientific tools and public entertainment devices, making microscopy a communal experience for the first time. The 1776 date places this instrument at the intersection of Pieter Teyler van der Hulst's lifetime collecting (he died 1778) and Martinus van Marum's early curatorship, making its provenance historically significant.",
